{"course_name": "The Legacy of Tradition I: The Growth of Science in the West", "description": "This course will consider the origins and development of science in the West.  What ancient principles are preserved? Beginning with early Greek \u201cproto scientific\u201d philosophy we will explore   emerging paradigms of science through a consideration and replication of great experiments that had significant impact by changing accepted world views. Before turning to the scientific and ontological revolution of the 16th and 17th centuries we will investigate the assumptions of pre-modern science. Philosophical, religious and scientific arguments will be studied and evaluated. Representative works of Bacon, Descartes, Galileo and Newton will be read to introduce the outlook of early modern science. The course will conclude with a survey of some contemporary scientific theories that evoke the legacy of tradition.\nOne lecture and laboratory each week.  In the lab students will, to the extent possible, replicate classic experiments from the history of science (list and descriptions of experiments in preparation).\n\r      ", "classification": "CCEX-SHU", "grading": "Ugrd Shanghai Graded", "class_name": "", "meet_data": "[{'start': '9.45 AM', 'end': '11.00 AM', 'day': 'Tue'}]", "notes": "This course satisfies the following Core Curriculum requirement: Science - Experimental Discovery.", "instructors": ["Sjursen, Harold"], "component": "Lecture", "number": "117", "loc_code": "SH", "session": {"start": " 09/01/201", "end": " 12/12/2014", "day": ""}, "college": "NYU Shanghai", "location": "", "units": "4", "is_open": true, "section": "001"}
